his research into sugar <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nucleotide\" title=\"Nucleotide\">nucleotides<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Carbohydrate\" title=\"Carbohydrate\">carbohydrate<\/a> metabolism, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Renal\" title=\"Renal\" class=\"mw-redirect\">renal<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hypertension\" title=\"Hypertension\">hypertension<\/a> has garnered international attention and fame and has led to significant progress in understanding, diagnosing and treating the congenital disease <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Galactosemia\" title=\"Galactosemia\">galactosemia<\/a>. Luis Leloir is buried in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/La_Recoleta_Cemetery\" title=\"La Recoleta Cemetery\">La Recoleta Cemetery<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Buenos_Aires\" title=\"Buenos Aires\">Buenos Aires<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Luis Federico Leloir","place_of_birth":"Paris ,  France","place_of_death":"Buenos Aires ,  Argentina","text":"Luis Federico Leloir , Chemistry, 1970","year":1970.0}